'''Laisser faire''' is [[French language|French]] for "[to] let [it] be", and is used in [[English language|English]] as a synonym to "hands-off approach" in a wide variety of contexts (for instance: "a ''laisser faire'' way of bringing up children"). 

The phrase should not be confused with [[laissez-faire]] (French: "[You should] let [us] be"), which also refers to a hands-off approach, but then specifically referring to the role of the [[government]] in the [[economy|economic life]] of the land.


